","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f995aa4b859d0cf0b0bdc85251f38ae52fee1678.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a35e6119002b7dd778e2ae0fb1e972a9ded8e019.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a30bebf76ae2f244ae392eed7db25e73e33a8f57.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"CheckBox\u0022, \u0022AsCombo\u0022, \u0022AsDateBox\u0022, \u0022AsTextBox\u0022, \u0022BlobControl\u0022, \u0022Checklist\u0022, \u0022ColorPicker\u0022, \u0022GroupBox\u0022, \u0022ImageBox\u0022, \u0022Label\u0022, \u0022MultiColumnAdapterFieldWrapp\u0022, \u0022RadioButton\u0022, and \u0022TagInput.\u0022 Each item is represented with a corresponding icon, indicating their function in a graphical user interface design context, likely for building forms or applications. The apparent purpose of this toolbox is to provide developers with ready-to-use UI widgets for application development.\n\n\n  \n After selecting the Field in the Entity tab, switch to the Widgets tab, and drag and drop  AsCombo  onto your screen. This will create your Field with the drop-down menu. \n   Item order setup \n By default, the items in the drop-down menu are ordered alphabetically. To change the order according to your custom criteria, follow these steps: \n   Choose the Data Structure \n Go to the Data Structure used in the Lookup for your drop-down menu. \n In our example, it is named  LookupPriority_Name_GetId . There is also a Data Structure named  Priority , but that is related to the Data Entity, not the Lookup: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6d1aa4e20f7a6b4b056e2beddab716615c2f214c.png]\nDescription: The image displays a hierarchical structure within a software application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The structure lists several items, including \u0022LookupPriority_Name_GetId\u0022 and \u0022LookupStatus_Name_GetId,\u0022 which are presented as expandable nodes. Below these items are three additional entries: \u0022Priority,\u0022 \u0022Status,\u0022 and \u0022Task.\u0022 This layout likely serves as a navigation pane or object hierarchy for managing various components related to task management or data lookups in the application.\n\n\n  \n   Create a new Sort Set \n Right-click on the Data Structure name, select  New  /  Sort set , and name it something like  ByOrder : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4606ba95bfb1c934b16e4b36c606428b8f63812e.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface from a software application, specifically a Model Browser for a project named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 It includes a hierarchical structure showing various components such as \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Constants,\u0022 and \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 with the last section expanding to reveal items like \u0022__spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022__system,\u0022 and \u0022Dimensions.\u0022 There is a context menu opened on the left side featuring options such as \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New,\u0022 \u0022Actions,\u0022 \u0022Convert To,\u0022 \u0022Move To Package,\u0022 \u0022Expand All,\u0022 and \u0022Edit item.\u0022 The apparent purpose of this interface is to manage data structures and entities within the application.\n\n\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8f8a4370cbedc1fafdea529c7e7617a982c275e8.png]\nDescription: The interface displayed is a property editor titled \u0022ByOrder,\u0022 with the sort set also named \u0022ByOrder.\u0022 It features an information section labeled \u0022(Info)\u0022 and a schema items section labeled \u0022(Schema Item).\u0022 The visible fields under \u0022(Schema Item)\u0022 include \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 which does not display a value, \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 shown as \u0022False,\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 where the value is \u0022ByOrder.\u0022 The purpose appears to be to manage sorting configurations for a data structure.\n\n\n  \n   Add Fields to your Sort Set \n Right-click on the newly created Sort Set, select  New  /  Sort Field : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7a702f2bf443dd8fc5d6ac05b386d2c7dc1814fb.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a Model Browser interface within a software application, specifically for a project named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The hierarchical structure includes sections labeled \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Constants,\u0022 with a focus on \u0022Data Structures.\u0022 Under \u0022Constants,\u0022 a subfolder named \u0022myapplication\u0022 is visible, containing entities, filter sets, and sort sets. The \u0022Sort Field\u0022 element is highlighted, showing an options menu with commands such as \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New,\u0022 and \u0022Actions.\u0022 The interface appears designed for organizing and managing data structures within the application.\n\n\n  \n   Set up your Sort Field \n In the Sort Field properties, select the  Entity  and  FieldName  according to the data source you want to use for the order: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:49:38"},"vector":[-0.03388317,-0.05301038,-0.05274822,0.008613723,-0.000429239,-0.0468963,-0.03895189,0.015266093,-0.0011750034,0.01776193,-0.002888999,-0.02613739,0.0025722631,0.028312432,0.046151664,0.0095568895,0.01530509,0.0018500333,0.02240606,0.02262049,-0.027236577,-0.0010169358,0.021560306,0.041964937,-0.0019088096,0.048246313,0.0055844714,-0.011833039,-0.04712433,0.027525371,0.016133761,-0.049968667,0.0023345095,-0.017780006,-0.0017798415,0.0011576235,0.01835715,-0.005413843,-0.04435751,0.027619662,-0.028383808,0.0142489,-0.0175674,0.0032897398,0.029945672,-0.04865958,-0.01222616,0.0066387546,-0.021858823,-0.047